            <head type="incipit">
               <supplied reason="XTF-compatibility">25, WILTON PLACE. S.W. ¶ June 3 /73 ¶ My dear Sir ¶  ¶ I have to thank you for your letter of the 23d March and for a parcel of Orchidaceous specimens per port which came just in time as I yesterday s...</supplied>
            </head>
            <p rend="number" xml:lang="en">73.06.03</p>
            <p rend="correspondent" xml:lang="en">From George Bentham</p>
            <p rend="location" xml:lang="en">RB MSS M3, Library, Royal Botanic Gardens Melbourne.</p>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; text-align: end; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <note xml:id="ftn1" type="footnote" n="1">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Annotated in pencil at top of letter by M: 'Lilia[s]'.</p>
               </note>
               <seg rend="form%20text" style="color: #2f5496; font-family: Times; ">25, WILTON PLACE. S.W.</seg>
            </p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; text-align: end; "
               xml:lang="en">June 3 /73</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">My dear Sir</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>I have to thank you for your letter of the 23d March and for a parcel of Orchidaceous specimens per port which came just in time as I yesterday sent off the <name key="Hydrocharideae">Hydrocharideae</name>
               <name key="Scitamineae">Scitamineae</name> and <name key="Orchideae">Orchideae</name> to the printer.<note xml:id="ftn2" type="footnote" n="2">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Bentham (1863-78), vol. 6, pp. 255-396.</p>
               </note> I had already determined the Epipogum which is the same as the Asiatic E. nutans.<note xml:id="ftn3" type="footnote" n="3">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <seg style="">
                        <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>
                     </seg>See Bentham (1863-78), vol. 6, p. 308, where he attributes the name <seg style="font-style: italic; ">E. guilfoylii</seg> to M; although M described the species in B73.03.02, p. 30, he did so without assigning a name.</p>
               </note> The Goodyeras are puzzling none of them true Goodyeras though I leave the two in the genus G. viridiflora is certainly the same as <name key="Georchis%20cordata">Georchis cordata</name> from [Khasia] and probly<note xml:id="ftn4" type="footnote" n="4">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>
                     <seg style="">probably?</seg>
                  </p>
               </note> the same as G. viridiflora Blume of which we have no specimen<note xml:id="ftn5" type="footnote" n="5">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <seg style="">
                        <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>
                     </seg>For the second species, Bentham retained M's name, <seg style="font-style: italic; ">G. polygonoides</seg>, B73.03.02, p. 29.</p>
               </note> — I have been obliged to take the characters of the <name key="Scitamineae">Scitamineae</name> from the proof slip you sent<note xml:id="ftn6" type="footnote" n="6">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>B73.03.02, pp. 24-7; see comment in Bentham (1863-78), vol. 6, p. 260.</p>
               </note> for the box per Hampshire (which arrived safely) only contained the <name key="Alpinia%20coerulea">Alpinia coerulea</name> the <name key="Musa">Musa</name> and the <name key="Curcuma">Curcuma</name> which we had already and the box per Somersetshire is not yet arrived</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>I have sent off by this post five more sheets of the Flora down to p. 208 Three more sheets are in type but the clean copies not yet struck off and this week's proofs will commence Monocotyledons</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>I trust you will have received safe the box of <name key="Orchideae">Orchideae</name> in which was also a copy of the new part of our Genera Plantarum<note xml:id="ftn7" type="footnote" n="7">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Bentham &amp; Hooker (1862-83), vol. 2, part 1.</p>
               </note>
            </p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>I hope that Mr Macleay will bring back better accounts of yourself and your goings-on<note xml:id="ftn8" type="footnote" n="8">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>George Macleay had delivered to M a case of deciduous trees from Kew; see M to J. Hooker, 25 March 1873. </p>
               </note> I should much like myself to have paid you a visit but I am far too old to think of it</p>
            <p rend="valediction"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; margin-left: 1.75in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: 0in; "
               xml:lang="en">Yours ever truly</p>
            <p rend="valediction"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; margin-left: 1.75in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: 0in; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>George Bentham</p>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">Baron Ferd v. Mueller</p>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">I follow Brown in including <name key="Apostasieae">Apostasieae</name> as a tribe of <name key="Orchideae">Orchideae</name>
               <note xml:id="ftn9" type="footnote" n="9">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Robert Brown (1773-1858); see Wallich (1830-32), vol. 1, pp. 74-75, quoting 'Brown MSS'.</p>
               </note>
               <name key="Apostasia">Apostasia</name> though anomalous as a whole yet piecemeal has the perianth of <name key="Thelymitra">Thelymitra</name> the habit of <name key="Corymbis">Corymbis</name> the ovary of <name key="Selenopodium">Selenopodium</name>
               <note xml:id="ftn10" type="footnote" n="10">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>
                     <seg style="font-style: italic; ">Selenipedium</seg>? <seg style="">Bentham (1863-78), vol. 6, p. 396 has </seg>
                     <seg style="font-style: italic; ">Selenipodium</seg>
                     <seg style="">. </seg>See Hooker (1865-1904), vol. 124, text accompanying t. 7573, for comments on the spelling of the genus name.</p>
               </note> and the stamens of <name key="Neuwiedia">Neuwiedia</name>
            </p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>I was disappointed in not finding among your <name key="Hydrocharideae">Hydrocharideae</name> an (<name key="Ottelia">Ottelia</name>?) which we have from Drummond and from the Wendu<note xml:id="ftn11" type="footnote" n="11">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Wando?</p>
               </note> river in Victoria from Roberston like a small slender variety of the common one but with a very thin membranous spatha and the capsule with only very thin small remains of the base of the perianth, our specimens are all in fruit only so that I am not certain of the genus.<note xml:id="ftn12" type="footnote" n="12">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>See Bentham (1863-78), vol. 6, p. 257, under <seg style="font-style: italic; ">O.? tenera</seg>.</p>
               </note> It would be well to search for it in your Victorian waters</p>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
